  "enhanced_information": "Methylphenidate is the drug of choice for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) as it stimulates the central nervous system, increasing dopamine and norepinephrine levels in the brain, which are crucial neurotransmitters for improving attention and focus in ADHD patients. This is supported by evidence paths linking dopamine and norepinephrine to the treatment of ADHD. Other options such as Haloperidol, an antipsychotic, and Imipramine, a tricyclic antidepressant, are less suitable. Haloperidol is primarily used for schizophrenia and not typically for ADHD, and while Imipramine is sometimes used off-label for ADHD, it is less effective than stimulants. Alprazolam, a benzodiazepine, is primarily used for anxiety disorders and is not indicated for ADHD, as it does not improve the core symptoms of attention or cognitive functions in ADHD patients."
